@Node "WHATIS_TAG" "Tag - What Is Tag? - (C) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design"

What Is Tag?
+------------+

Tag is an Amigaguide filelist creator for TransAmiga BBS s/w ((C) S.Radwan 94-96)
which is both easy to use and extremely fast.

The reason I wrote this is because I saw a Guide creator written by Tom Pereira
(Hello m8 how's life with Zeus?) in rexx but it was never released and was given
to Neil Barrett (TA UK support BBS) only (custom coded). Then one night I saw
Guide-X, well this was ok, but I guessed it was coded in Arexx and would be slow
and it didn't do half of the stuff Tag can do - thus Tag was born!

Tag is coded in 100% C and is therefore damned fast at it's job.

It has many options (see @{" Usage " Link "USAGE!_TAG"}) and creates guide files full of colour,
life and with the ability to FREQ files from the originating BBS!

@EndNode

@Node "REQUIR_TAG" "Tag - System Requirements - (C) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design"

System Requirements
+-----------------+

1) Amiga OS1.2+

2) TransAmiga BBS Software Installed v1.x ->

3) A Filebase ;).

@EndNode

@Node "INSTAL_TAG" "Tag - How To Install Tag - (C) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design"

How Do I Install Tag?
+---------------------+

Follow these easy steps and you'll have no problems.

Copy the main "tag" executable to any path you like (reccomend C: or BBS:Bin).

Then you can use it at your disposal, it is though reccomended that you execute
Tag along with the standard file list creators you have running, e.g. in a
midnight script and create an entry for it on your BBS where the users may
download it.

@EndNode

@Node "USAGE!_TAG" "Tag - Usage - (C) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design"

Usage
+---+

Typing "Tag" or "Tag ?" will result in the following being displayed to STDOUT:

-><---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tag v1.1 - (c) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design Production
Coded In 100% Pure C =)!

Usage: 

	Tag <File.Cfg Path> <Guide File Destination Path> [options]

	Options:

	Syntax   Description / Available Modes                         Default
	------   -----------   ---------------                         -------
	-v[x]    Verbose On?   x=1 (True), x=0 (False)                 1
	-b[path] Banner Path   path=Banner path, nopath = no banner    None
	-<[x]    From Access   x=Access lvl limit [0-255] to start at  0
	->[x]    To Access     x=Access lvl limit [0-255] to end at    10
	-a[add]  Mail Address  Mail address to create FREQ's for       2.250.602.0
	-r[x]    Read Access   ALSO check access limits against READ   0
	                       access of area aswell as LIBRARY access
	                       x=1 (True), x=0 (False)
	-f[flag] Flags Setup   flag=-------- Flags that must be set for
	                       area to be included in guide            --------

-><---------------------------------------------------------------------------

-v turns verbosity on or off, turning it off will result in each area being
   processed 0.04 seconds faster :) (Wow!)  -v0 = off, -v1 = on.

-b allows you to add a text file to the top of the guide file, this might
   be a BBS advertisment for example. e.g. -bbbs:misc/digitald.displayme.

-< specifys the starting level of the access level limiter. e.g. -<5.

-> specifys the end level of the access level limiter. e.g. ->10.
   Having start at 5 and end at 10 means that any area access level falling
   inbetween 5 & 10 (inclusive) will be included, anything outside will be
   scrapped.

-a specifys your (fidonet) mail address. Following the format of:
   ZONE.NET.NODE.POINT, e.g. -a2.250.602.0 (2:250/602.0).
   * the ".0" if you are a node IS important.
   This address will be used to place FREQs (File Requests) from the reader.
   The requests will be placed in the "Outbound:" path (if it is assigned)
   and will be in a filename called "<address>.REQ" (2.250.602.0.REQ).
   Next time the reader calls the node with Trapdoor/etc. the request will
   be issued just like it would normally.

-r toggles the read access checker on off, when Tag checks to see if the
   current area is within the access limits it, as default, only checks
   the library access level. However you can tell it to also check the
   READ access level. e.g. -r1 = on, -r0 = off.

-f specifys which flags must be set for the area to be included in the
   AmigaGuide file. e.g. -f-XXX----.

Examples of usage:

tag bbs:configs/file.cfg bbs:filelist.guide -v1 -bbbs:bbs.displayme -<0 ->10
-a2.250.602.0 -f--------

[ would create a guidefile located at bbs:filelist.guide with all file areas
  falling under the access level restriction of between 0 and 10 (inclusive)
  and falling under the flag restriction of "--------", with verbosity on and
  all FREQs being directed to 2:250/602.0 ]


* Limitations/Notes *

TAG will not support any more than 800 areas (so Tag will work at 4096 stack).

TAG uses 80 bytes per area and operates (as said above) nicely in a 4096
stack environment.

TAG frees up all memory upon exit/memory allocaton failure.

That's it!

* *

@EndNode

@Node "HISTOR_TAG" "Tag - History - (C) S.Gillibrand 1996 - Digital Design"

History
+-----+

*Version 1.0
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Date       Details

23-May-96  First Public Release Of Tag.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Version 1.1
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Date       Details

28-May-96  v1.1 - Fixes & Improvements!

BUGFIX, Tag would crash if you had an ODD number of file areas (e.g. 79/13/35).
        (Arrgh!) now this is fixed, sorry about that ppl!
BUGFIX, Tag now only regards the "X" (ON) flag as important when checking for
        access to an area, (e.g. XXXXXXXX would include areas that have --X-----).
NEWOPT, Now you can specify to list ONLY files that are up to (including) [x]
        amount days old.
.MISC., General code tweaking applied ;).
.MISC., Corrected *TINY* error in this guide file.
*NOTE*, Due to the format of the TransAmiga filebase commenting and FILE_ID.DIZ
        usage it is *IMPOSSIBLE* to differentiate between them to 100% accuracy!
        Therefore if you are listing files in "-n" mode only the FIRST filebase
        comment will be printed.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@EndNode

